            <span class="MItem DateCreated">
               Posted on 2019-07-23 04:38:25            </span>
                        <span class="MItem"> <span title="Edited July 23, 2019 8:32PM by aikiwolf." class="DateUpdated">edited July 2019</span> </span>                        <span class="Voter"><a href="/entry/signin?Target=discussion%2F5197%2Fhow-to-manually-refresh-smartshare-file-list-on-lg-4k-tv" class="VoteUp SignInPopup"><i class="ArrowSprite SpriteUp" rel="nofollow"><i>Vote Up</i></i></a><span>0</span><a href="/entry/signin?Target=discussion%2F5197%2Fhow-to-manually-refresh-smartshare-file-list-on-lg-4k-tv" class="VoteDown SignInPopup"><i class="ArrowSprite SpriteDown" rel="nofollow"><i>Vote Down</i></i></a></span>                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="Item-BodyWrap">
                    <div class="Item-Body">
                        <div class="Message">
                            <div>As I mentioned in the original post, I can refresh manually within the SmartShare program on my PC. And I can confirm the changes are in the list of shared files/folders. However, the LG TV only displays the old list from before the changes. That's why I said it sounds like the LG has some kind of cache that its reading from, rather than "looking" for the actually available content. <br /></div><div><br /></div><div>Furthermore, I might see different folder lists on the LG depending on the navigation method, even though I end up in the same location. For example, after selecting the networked location on my LG and then choosing "Photos &amp; Videos": If I go to "All Folders," I might not see the updated list, but if I go to "Videos" and then "Videos by Folder," I might. If the list is being read purely from the PC, then I would expect the folder list to be identical with my setup, as would any files without those folders. But it's not. Even if I then opened the same folder using both methods, the file list would differ if there were updates (i.e., first method doesn't show the changes, but the second method does). Thus, it acts like the LG is drawing from a cache, and the second method didn't have one established yet because I never use that method and the LG then needs to "look" for the current folders/files.</div><div><br /></div><div>Now, if I then update files/folders on the PC again, neither method will display the newest updates, presumably because both methods now do have a cache. So the question remains: How do I force the LG to display the "live" list of files/folders?<br /></div>                        </div>
                        <div class="Reactions"></div><div class="ReactionRecord"></div>                      
                    </div>
